<section xml:id="section-elimination">

    <title>Elimination</title>

    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-solve-systems-of-equations" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-application-of-systems-of-equations" /></li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <introduction>
        <p>We have learned how to solve a system of linear equations by substitution. In this section, we will learn a second symbolic method for solving systems of linear equations.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="ova8GSmPV4o"/>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Systems of Equations by Elimination</title>

        <example xml:id="example-system-of-equations-elimination-intro">
        <p>Michelle wants to invest <dollar/><m>10{,}000</m> in two accounts. She would like to put <dollar/><m>1{,}200</m> more in Account A than Account B. How much money should she invest in each account?</p>

        <p>Assume Michelle will invest <m>x</m> dollars in Account A, and <m>y</m> dollars in Account B. Based on the given conditions, we can write the following system of equations:<md>
            <mrow>
                \left\{
                    \begin{alignedat}{4}
                    x \amp {}+{} \amp  y \amp {}={} \amp 10000 \\
                    x \amp {}-{} \amp  y \amp {}={} \amp 1200 \\
                    \end{alignedat}
                \right.
            </mrow></md></p>

        <p>We could solve this system by substitution as we learned in the last section, but there is an easier method. First, we need to learn a new property.</p>

         <p>If we have two equations, <m>1+5=6</m> and <m>3+8=11</m>, we can add the left and right sides together to create a new equation:<md>
            <mrow>1+5+3+8\amp=6+11</mrow>
            <mrow>17\amp=17</mrow>
        </md>Since the two original equations are true, the new equation is also true. Similarly, we can add the two equations in our system:<md>
            <mrow>x+y\amp=10000</mrow>
            <mrow>x-y\amp=1200</mrow>
            <intertext>When we add the left and right sides we get:</intertext>
            <mrow>x+x+y-y\amp=10000+1200</mrow>
            <mrow>2x\amp=11200</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=5600</mrow>
        </md></p>

        <p>To finish solving this system of equations, we need the value of <m>y</m>. We will find it like we did in the substitution method, by replacing <m>x</m> with <m>5600</m> in either equation. We will choose the first equation:<md>
            <mrow>x+y\amp=10000</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{5600}+y\amp=10000</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=4400</mrow>
        </md>To check the solution, we need to substitute <m>x=5600</m> and <m>y=4400</m> in each equation:<md>
            <mrow>x-y\amp=1200</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{5600}-\substitute{4400}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}1200</mrow>
            <mrow>1200\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}1200</mrow>
            <intertext>and</intertext>
            <mrow>x+y\amp=10000</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{5600}+\substitute{4400}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}10000</mrow>
            <mrow>10000\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}10000</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
        <p>We have verified that our solution is correct. In summary, Michelle should invest <dollar/><m>5{,}600</m> in Account A, and <dollar/><m>4{,}400</m> in Account B.</p>
        </example>

        <remark><p>This method worked in <xref ref="example-system-of-equations-elimination-intro">Example</xref> because <m>y</m> and <m>-y</m> add to zero. Once the <m>y</m> terms were eliminated we were able to solve for <m>x</m>. This method is called the <term>elimination method</term>. Some textbooks call it the <term>addition method</term>, because we added the two equations to eliminate a variable.</p>
    
        <p>If neither variable will immediately be eliminated, we can still use this method but it will require that we first adjust one or both of the equations.</p>
        </remark>

        <p> Let's look at an example where we need to adjust one of the equations.</p>


        <example xml:id="example-system-of-equations-elimination-intro-build-one-equation">
            <title>Building One Equation</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the elimination method.
                    <md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            3x \amp {}-{} \amp  4y \amp {}={} \amp 2 \\
                            5x \amp {}+{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp 18 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To start, we want to see whether it will be easier to eliminate <m>x</m> or <m>y</m>. We see that the coefficients of <m>x</m> in each equation are <m>3</m> and <m>5</m>, and the coefficients of <m>y</m> are <m>-4</m> and <m>8</m>. Because <m>8</m> is a multiple of <m>4</m> and the coefficients already have opposite signs, the <m>y</m> variable will be easier to eliminate.
                </p>

                <p>To eliminate the <m>y</m> terms, we will multiply each side of the first equation by <m>2</m> so that we will have <m>-8y</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3x-4y\amp=2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{2}(3x-4y)\amp=\multiplyleft{2}(2)</mrow>
                        <mrow>6x-8y\amp=4</mrow>
                    </md>
                    We now have an equivalent system of equations where the <m>y</m> terms can be eliminated:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                6x \amp {}-{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp 4 \\
                                5x \amp {}+{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp 18 \\
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Next, adding the left and right sides of the equations, we get:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>6x+5x-8y+8y\amp=4+18</mrow>
                        <mrow>6x+5x\amp=4+18</mrow>
                        <mrow>11x\amp=22</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    To solve for <m>y</m>, we will substitute <m>2</m> for <m>x</m> into either of the original equations or the new one. We will use the original first equation, <m>3x-4y=2</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3x-4y\amp=2</mrow>
                        <mrow>3(\substitute{2})-4y\amp=2</mrow>
                        <mrow>6-4y\amp=2</mrow>
                        <mrow>-4y\amp=-4</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=1</mrow>
                    </md>

                    Our solution is <m>x=2</m> and <m>y=1</m>. We will check this in both of the original equations:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>5x+8y\amp=18</mrow>
                        <mrow>5(\substitute{2})+8(\substitute{1})\amp\stackrel{?}{=}18</mrow>
                        <mrow>10+8\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}18</mrow>
                        <intertext>and</intertext>
                        <mrow>3x-4y\amp=2</mrow>
                        <mrow>3(\substitute{2})-4(\substitute{1})\amp\stackrel{?}{=}2</mrow>
                        <mrow>6-4\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    The solution to this system is <m>(2,1)</m> and the solution set is <m>\{(2,1)\}</m>. 
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Here's an example where we have to build both equations.</p>

        <example>
            <title>Building Both Equations</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the elimination method.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                2x \amp {}+{} \amp  3y \amp {}={} \amp 10 \\
                                -3x \amp {}+{} \amp  5y \amp {}={} \amp -15 \\
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To start, we see that we cannot eliminate the <m>x</m> or the <m>y</m> variable by building a single equation so we will need to build both.</p>

                <p>The terms containing <m>x</m> already have opposite signs, so we will choose to eliminate the <m>x</m> variable. The least common multiple of <m>2</m> and <m>3</m> is <m>6</m>. We can multiply the first equation by 3 and the second equation by 2 to get <m>6x</m> and <m>-6x</m>. Here are the steps to multiply the first equation by <m>3</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x+3y\amp=10</mrow>
                    <mrow>\multiplyleft{3}(2x+3y)\amp=\multiplyleft{3}(10)</mrow>
                    <mrow>6x+9y\amp=30</mrow>
                </md>
                and the second equation by <m>2</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>-3x+5y\amp=-15</mrow>
                    <mrow>\multiplyleft{2}(-3x+5y)\amp=\multiplyleft{2}(-15)</mrow>
                    <mrow>-6x+10y\amp=-30</mrow>
                </md>
                The system can now be re-written as the equivalent system:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                6x \amp {}+{} \amp  9y \amp {}={} \amp 30 \\
                                -6x \amp {}+{} \amp  10y \amp {}={} \amp -30 \\
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>At this point we can add the equations and solve for <m>y</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>6x+9y+(-6x)+10y\amp=30+(-30)</mrow>
                        <mrow>19y\amp=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=0</mrow>
                    </md>
                To solve for <m>x</m>, we'll replace <m>y</m> with <m>0</m> in <m>2x+3y=10</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2x+3y\amp=10</mrow>
                        <mrow>2x+3\substitute{(0)}\amp=10</mrow>
                        <mrow>2x\amp=10</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=5</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>We'll check the system using <m>x=5</m> and <m>y=0</m> in each of the original equations:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2x+3y\amp=10</mrow>
                        <mrow>2(\substitute{5})+3(\substitute{0})\amp\stackrel{?}{=}10</mrow>
                        <mrow>10+0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}10</mrow>
                        <intertext>and</intertext>
                        <mrow>-3x+5y\amp=-15</mrow>
                        <mrow>-3(\substitute{5})+5(\substitute{0})\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-15</mrow>
                        <mrow>-15+0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-15</mrow>
                    </md>
                The system's solution is <m>(5,0)</m> and the solution set is <m>\{(5,0)\}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <warning><p>
            We will avoid building equations with fractions because that would make the equations more complicated than the ones we started with.
        </p></warning>

</subsection>

<subsection>
        <title>Solving Special Systems of Equations with Elimination</title>

        <p>Remember the two special cases we encountered when solving by graphing and substitution? Let's see what happens when we use the elimination method on each of the special cases.</p>

        <example>
            <title>A System with Infinitely Many Solutions</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the elimination method.
                    <md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            3x \amp {}+{} \amp  4y \amp {}={} \amp 5 \\
                            6x \amp {}+{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp 10 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow></md></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To eliminate the <m>x</m> terms, we multiply each term in the first equation by <m>-2</m>, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>3x+4y\amp=5</mrow>
                    <mrow>\multiplyleft{-2}(3x+4y)\amp=\multiplyleft{-2}(5)\</mrow>
                    <mrow>-6x-8y\amp=-10</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>Now we have an equivalent system of:
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            {-6x} \amp {}-{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp {-10} \\
                            6x \amp {}+{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp 10 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.   
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>We might notice that the equations look very similar. Adding the respective sides of the equation, we have:
                <md>
                    <mrow>-6x-8y+6x+8y\amp=-10+10</mrow>
                    <mrow>0\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>Both of the variables have been eliminated. Since the statement <m>0=0</m> is true, the two equations represent the same line. (They are equivalent because one is a multiple of the other.) Since they are coinciding lines, the system has infinitely many solutions, which are all points on the line <m>3x+4y=5</m>. We write the solution set as <m>\{(x,y)\mid 3x+4y=5\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <title>A System with No Solution</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the elimination method.
                    <md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            3x \amp {}+{} \amp  4y \amp {}={} \amp 6 \\
                            6x \amp {}+{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp 10 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow></md></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To eliminate the <m>x</m> terms, we will multiply each side of the first equation by <m>-2</m>, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>3x+4y\amp=6</mrow>
                    <mrow>\multiplyleft{-2}(3x+4y)\amp=\multiplyleft{-2}(6)</mrow>
                    <mrow>-6x-8y\amp=-12</mrow>
                </md>We can then write this system as:<md alignment="alignat">
                    <mrow>{-6x} \amp {}-{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp {-12}</mrow>
                    <mrow>6x \amp {}+{} \amp  8y \amp {}={} \amp 10</mrow>
                    <intertext>Adding the equations we have:</intertext>
                    <mrow>\amp\amp{-6}x-8y+6x+8y\amp=-12+10</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp\amp0\amp=-2</mrow>
                </md>Again, both of the variables have been eliminated. In this case, the statement <m>0=-2</m> is false, so the system has no solution. The two equations represent parallel lines and we write the solution set as <m>\emptyset</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>
    
    <subsection>
        <title>Choosing Whether to Use Substitution or Elimination</title>
            
            <p>You'll notice that in each of the examples above, both equations were in standard form, <m>Ax+By=C</m>. If none of the coefficients are equal to one then it is easier to use the elimination method. If there is a coefficient of one then it is a matter of preference. If one of the equations is not in standard form, substitution may be easier. Let's look at an example where we determine whether it will be simpler to use substitution or elimination.
            </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the method of your choice.
                    <md>
                    <mrow>
                    \left\{
                        \begin{alignedat}{3}
                        -\frac{1}{3}y\amp = \frac{1}{15}x + \frac{1}{5} \\
                        \frac{5}{2}x-y\amp = 6 \\
                        \end{alignedat}
                    \right.
                    </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>First, we will remove the fractions by multiplying each equation by the LCD. For the first equation, we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>-\frac{1}{3}y\amp=\frac{1}{15}x+\frac{1}{5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{15}\left(-\frac{1}{3}y\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{15}\left(\frac{1}{15}x+\frac{1}{5}\right)</mrow>
                        <mrow>-5y\amp=x+3</mrow>
                    </md>
                For the second equation, we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{5}{2}x-y\amp=6</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{2}\left(\frac{5}{2}x-y\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{2}(6)</mrow>
                        <mrow>5x-2y\amp=12</mrow>
                    </md>
                Now the system of equations can be written as:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            -5y\amp=x+3 \\
                            5x-2y\amp=12 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                We could put the the first equation into standard form and use elimination. However, the <m>x</m>-variable in the first equation has a coefficient of one, so we will use the substitution method. Solving for <m>x</m> in the first equation we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            -5y\amp=x+3 \\
                            -5y\subtractright{3}\amp=x+3\subtractright{3}\ \\
                            -5y-3\amp=x \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        </mrow>
                        <intertext>Substituting <m>-5y-3</m> for <m>x</m> in the second equation we have:</intertext>
                        <mrow>5(\substitute{-5y-3})-2y\amp=12</mrow>
                        <mrow>-25y-15-2y\amp=12</mrow>
                        <mrow>-27y-15\amp=12</mrow>
                        <mrow>-27y\amp=27</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-1</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Substituting <m>-1</m> for <m>y</m>, we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>-5(\substitute{-1})-3\amp=x</mrow>
                        <mrow>5-3\amp=x</mrow>
                        <mrow>2\amp=x</mrow>
                    </md>
                The solution is <m>(2,-1)</m>. Checking the solution is left as an exercise.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <remark><p>To summarize, if a variable is already isolated or has a coefficient of one, consider using the substitution method. If both equations are in standard form or none of the coefficients are equal to one, we suggest using the elimination method.
        </p></remark>
    
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Setting up and Solving Applications of Systems of Equations</title>
            <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Alicia is on a meal plan and needs to consume <m>600</m> calories and <m>20</m> grams of fat for breakfast. A small avocado contains <m>300</m> calories and <m>30</m> grams of fat. She has bagels that contain <m>400</m> calories and <m>8</m> grams of fat. Write and solve a system of equations to determine how many bagels and avocados she should eat.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To write this system of equations, we first need to define our variables. Let <m>A</m> be the number of avocados consumed and let <m>B</m> be the number of bagels consumed. In our first equation, we will add the number of calories in the avocados and bagels:
                    <me>300A+400B=600</me>
                Similarly, in our second equation, we will add the grams of fat:
                    <me>30A+8B=20</me>
                Our system of equations looks like this:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                300A \amp {}+{} \amp  400B \amp {}={} \amp 600 \\
                                30A \amp {}+{} \amp  8B \amp {}={} \amp 20 \\
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>Since none of the coefficients are equal to one, it will be easier to use the elimination method to solve this system. Looking at the terms <m>300A</m> and <m>30A</m>, we can eliminate the <m>A</m> variable if we multiply the second equation by <m>-10</m> to get <m>-300A</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 30A + 8B\amp=20</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{-10}(30A+8B)\amp=\multiplyleft{-10}(20)</mrow>
                        <mrow>-300A-80B\amp=-200</mrow>
                    </md>
                An equivalent system can now be written as:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                300A \amp {}+{} \amp  400B \amp {}={} \amp 600 \\
                                -300A \amp {}-{} \amp  80B \amp {}={} \amp -200 \\
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                When we add the two equations together we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>300A+400B-300A-80B\amp=600-200</mrow>
                        <mrow>320B\amp=400</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{320B}{320}\amp=\divideunder{400}{320}</mrow>
                        <mrow>B\amp=\frac{5}{4}</mrow>
                    </md>
                We now know that she can eat <m>\frac{5}{4}</m> bagels (or one and one-quarter bagels). To determine the number of avocados, we will replace <m>B</m> with <m>\frac{5}{4}</m> in either of our equations. We will use the first one:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>300A+400B\amp=600</mrow>
                        <mrow>300A+400\left(\substitute{\frac{5}{4}}\right)\amp=600</mrow>
                        <mrow>300A+500\amp=600</mrow>
                        <mrow>300A+500\subtractright{500}\amp=600\subtractright{500}</mrow>
                        <mrow>300A\amp=100</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{300A}{300}\amp=\divideunder{100}{300}</mrow>
                        <mrow>A\amp=\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>To check this result, we'll replace <m>B</m> with <m>\frac{5}{4}</m> and <m>A</m> with <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> in each of the original equations:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>300A+400B=600</mrow>
                        <mrow>300\left(\substitute{\frac{1}{3}}\right)+400\left(\substitute{\frac{5}{4}}\right)\amp\stackrel{?}{=}600</mrow>
                        <mrow>100+500\amp={\checkmark}{=}600</mrow>
                        <intertext>and</intertext>
                        <mrow>30A+8B\amp=20</mrow>
                        <mrow>30\left(\substitute{\frac{1}{3}}\right)+8\left(\substitute{\frac{5}{4}}\right)\amp\stackrel{?}{=}20</mrow>
                        <mrow>10+10\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}20</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>In summary, Alicia can eat <m>\1frac{1}{4}</m> bagels and <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> of an avocado in order to consume exactly <m>600</m> calories and <m>20</m> grams of fat.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

  <!-- capitalize north and south? -->
        <example xml:id="example-solving-system-of-equations-student-demographics">
            <statement>
                <p>A college used to have a north campus with <m>6{,}000</m> students and a south campus with <m>15{,}000</m> students. The percentage of students at the north campus who identified as LGBTQ was three times the percentage at the south campus. After the merge, <m>5.5\%</m> of students identify as LGBTQ. What percentage of students on each campus identified as LGBTQ before the merge?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will define <m>N</m> as the percentage of students at the north campus and <m>S</m> as the percentage of students at the south campus that identified as LGBTQ. Since the percentage of students at the north campus was three times the percentage at the south campus, we have:
                    <me>N=3S</me>
                For our second equation, we will multiply the population of each campus by the respective percentage of LGBTQ-identifying students. When we combine the two campuses, we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>6000N+15000S\amp=21000(0.055)</mrow>
                    </md>
                    We write the system as:
                    <me>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{3}
                            N\amp=3S \\
                            6000N+15000S\amp=21000(0.055)
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p>Because the first equation is already solved for <m>N</m>, we will use the substitution method. We will replace <m>N</m> in our second equation with <m>3S</m> and solve for <m>S</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>6000N+15000S\amp=1155</mrow>
                        <mrow>6000(\substitute{3S})+15000S\amp=1155</mrow>
                        <mrow>18000S+15000S\amp=1155</mrow>
                        <mrow>33000S\amp=1155</mrow>
                        <mrow>S\amp=\frac{1155}{33000}</mrow>
                        <mrow>S\amp=0.035</mrow>
                    </md>                
                </p>
                <p>As a final step, we can determine <m>N</m> using the first equation:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>N\amp=3S</mrow>
                        <mrow>N\amp=3(0.035)</mrow>
                        <mrow>N\amp=0.105</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>Before the merge, the percentage of LGBTQ-identifying students was <m>10.5\%</m> at the north campus and <m>3.5\%</m> at the south campus.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Kim is designing a rectangular garden. The garden's length must be <m>10</m> feet shorter than twice the width, and the garden's perimeter must be <m>70</m> feet. How long should the garden's length and width be?</p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>Let the garden's length be <m>l</m> feet, and its width be <m>w</m> feet. Recall that the perimeter of a rectangle can be calculated by <m>P=2l+2w</m>. Using the given conditions, we can write the system of equations:<md>
                 <mrow>
                    \left\{
                        \begin{alignedat}{4}
                        l \amp= 2w-10 \\
                        2l+2w \amp= 70 \\
                        \end{alignedat}
                    \right.
                </mrow></md></p>

                <p>Since <m>l=2w-10</m>, we can substitute <m>2w-10</m> for <m>l</m> in the second equation, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>2l+2w \amp= 70</mrow>
                    <mrow>2(\substitute{2w-10})+2w \amp= 70</mrow>
                    <mrow>4w-20+2w \amp= 70</mrow>
                    <mrow>6w-20\amp=70</mrow>
                    <mrow>6w\amp=90</mrow>
                    <mrow>w\amp=15</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>Once we know <m>w=15</m>, we substitute <m>w=15</m> into the first equation <m>l=2w-10</m>, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>l \amp= 2w-10</mrow>
                    <mrow>l \amp= 2(\substitute{15})-10</mrow>
                    <mrow>l \amp= 30-10</mrow>
                    <mrow>l \amp= 20</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>The solution is <m>l=20\text{ and }w=15</m>. The garden's length should be <m>20</m> feet, and its width should be <m>15</m> feet.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

